{
    "identity": "nprot-134",
    "title": "Multicopy suppressor screen",
    "content": [
        {
            "header": "Introduction",
            "content": "To identify mutations that restore the activity of a defective ammonium transporter, natural suppressors or supprssors generated by mutagenesis can be identified."
        },
        {
            "header": "Procedure",
            "content": "1)  Select suppressor mutants from the 31019b yeast strain\n\\(1)\ncarrying the high copy number plasmid pDR-AtAMT1;1Thr460Ala by growing at 28\u00baC for 8 days on solid YNB medium supplemented with 3% glucose and 2 mM ammonium chloride. \r\n\n\n2)  Pick suppressors and amplify in liquid YNB medium supplemented with 3% glucose and 2 mM ammonium. \r\n\n\n3)  Isolate plasmid from yeast by CTAB extraction and use for _E. coli_ transformation. \r\n\n\n4)  Amplify plasmids in _E. coli_, isolate and sequence."
        },
        {
            "header": "Anticipated Results",
            "content": "When an inactive transporter **Trans** is subjected to a multi-copy suppressor screen, point mutations \\(single base changes, primarily) may occur spontaneously in the sequence of **Trans**. Such a spontaneous mutation occurs first in a single plasmid molecule, yielding a single **Trans-Mut** sequence. If **Trans-Mut** does not contribute to transport and growth, the cell will die and the sequence will be lost. If **Trans-Mut** does improve transport, it will initially function in \\(**Trans**)<sub>2</sub>\\(**Trans-Mut**)<sub>1</sub> complexes, as **Trans** is present in vast excess. If activity is sufficient to lead to growth, **Trans-Mut** will replicate sufficiently to be observed by plasmid DNA sequencing. Reversion to the wild-type sequence in a single plasmid molecule would yield \\(**Trans**)<sub>2</sub>\\(**wt**)<sub>1</sub> and \\(**Trans**)<sub>1</sub>\\(**wt**)<sub>2</sub> complexes at the outset \\(**wt**<sub>3</sub> would be a sufficiently small portion of the population that it would not contribute to growth). The absence of wild-type revertants from the suppressor screens suggests that these complexes are inactive."
        },
        {
            "header": "References",
            "content": "\\(1) Marini, A. M., Soussi-Boudekou, S., Vissers, S. &amp; Andr&#xE9;, B. A family of ammonium transporters in Saccharomyces cerevisiae. _Mol. Cell. Biol._ **17**, 4282-4293 \\(1997)."
        }
    ],
